# Chargebee Webhook — Auto-Promote Payment Source to Primary

A lightweight Node.js server that listens for Chargebee's `payment_source_added`
webhook event and automatically promotes the newly added payment method to Primary.

---

## What This Does

```
Customer adds a new card in Chargebee
          ↓
Chargebee fires a webhook → payment_source_added
          ↓
This server receives the webhook
          ↓
Calls Chargebee API → Assign Payment Role → role: primary
          ↓
New card is now the Primary payment method ✓
```

---

## Prerequisites

| Requirement | Version | Download |
|-------------|---------|----------|
| Node.js | v18 or higher | [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org) |
| ngrok account | Free tier | [ngrok.com](https://ngrok.com) |
| Chargebee test site | Any | [chargebee.com](https://chargebee.com) |

---

## Project Structure

```
chargebee-webhook/
├── index.js        → the main server (all the logic lives here)
├── package.json    → project metadata + dependencies
└── node_modules/   → auto-generated after npm install (don't edit this)
```

---

## Setup & Running Locally

### Step 1 — Clone or download this project

If you have the files already, skip this. Otherwise:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/chargebee-webhook.git
cd chargebee-webhook
```

### Step 2 — Install dependencies

```bash
npm install
```

This installs `express` and `axios` (listed in package.json).
A `node_modules/` folder will appear — that's normal.

### Step 3 — Start the server

```bash
node index.js
```

You should see:
```
Chargebee webhook listener running on port 3000
```

Leave this terminal running.

### Step 4 — Expose your local server with ngrok

Open a **second terminal** and run:

```bash
npx ngrok http 3000
```

You'll see a public URL like:
```
Forwarding   https://abc123.ngrok-free.app → http://localhost:3000
```

Copy that `https://` URL — you'll need it in the next step.

> **First time using ngrok?** You need a free account.
> Run this once after signing up:
> ```bash
> npx ngrok config add-authtoken YOUR_TOKEN_HERE
> ```
> Get your token at [dashboard.ngrok.com/get-started/your-authtoken](https://dashboard.ngrok.com/get-started/your-authtoken)

### Step 5 — Register the webhook in Chargebee

1. Log into your Chargebee test site
2. Go to **Settings → Configure Chargebee → API Keys & Webhooks → Webhooks**
3. Click **Add Webhook**
4. Fill in:
   - **Webhook Name**: `auto-promote-primary`
   - **Webhook URL**: `https://abc123.ngrok-free.app/webhook` ← your ngrok URL + `/webhook`
   - **API Version**: `V2`
   - **Events**: enable `payment_source_added`
5. Click **Create**

### Step 6 — Test it

Add a card to any customer in your Chargebee test site.

In your first terminal, you should see:
```
[2026-07-22T15:20:00.197Z] Event received: payment_source_added
  Customer : cus_xxxxx
  Source   : pm_xxxxx (card)
  → Assigning PRIMARY role to source pm_xxxxx for customer cus_xxxxx
  ✓ Done — pm_xxxxx is now Primary.
```

---

## Configuration

The server reads credentials from environment variables.
If not set, it falls back to the defaults hardcoded in `index.js`.

| Variable | Description | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| `CHARGEBEE_SITE` | Your Chargebee subdomain only | `lathuworld25-test` |
| `CHARGEBEE_API_KEY` | Your Chargebee API key (test or live) | `test_xxxxxxxxxxxx` |
| `PORT` | Port the server listens on | `3000` (default) |

### Setting environment variables (recommended for security)

```bash
export CHARGEBEE_SITE="lathuworld25-test"
export CHARGEBEE_API_KEY="test_xxxxxxxxxxxx"
node index.js
```

> ⚠️ **Important:** Set `CHARGEBEE_SITE` to just the subdomain.
> Do NOT include `.chargebee.com` — the code adds that automatically.
>
> ✅ `lathuworld25-test`
> ❌ `lathuworld25-test.chargebee.com`

---

## How to Stop the Server

- In Terminal 1 (node server) → press `Ctrl + C`
- In Terminal 2 (ngrok) → press `Ctrl + C`

---

## Stopping & Restarting

Every time you restart ngrok, you get a **new public URL**.
You'll need to update the webhook URL in Chargebee each time.

To avoid this, you can:
- Get a fixed ngrok domain (ngrok free tier includes one static domain)
- Or deploy to a cloud service (Render, Railway, Fly.io — all have free tiers)

---

## Common Errors & Fixes

| Error | Cause | Fix |
|-------|-------|-----|
| `Cannot find module 'express'` | Dependencies not installed | Run `npm install` |
| `fetch failed` | Wrong site name format | Make sure `CHARGEBEE_SITE` has no `.chargebee.com` |
| `Hostname does not match certificate` | `CHARGEBEE_SITE` env var has full domain | Run `unset CHARGEBEE_SITE` then restart |
| `authentication failed` (ngrok) | No ngrok account linked | Run `npx ngrok config add-authtoken YOUR_TOKEN` |
| No response in terminal | Webhook URL not saved correctly in Chargebee | Check the URL ends with `/webhook` |

---

## Next Step — Add the Expired Card Guard

Once this basic flow is working, you can make it smarter:
only promote the new card if the **current Primary is expired or invalid**.

Add this block inside the `payment_source_added` handler in `index.js`,
right before the `assignPrimaryRole()` call:

```javascript
// Fetch the customer's current primary source
const customerData = await chargebeeRequest(`/customers/${customerId}`);
const primarySourceId = customerData.customer?.primary_payment_source_id;

if (primarySourceId) {
  const sourceData = await chargebeeRequest(`/payment_sources/${primarySourceId}`);
  const existing = sourceData.payment_source;

  const isExpired =
    existing?.status === "expired" ||
    existing?.status === "invalid" ||
    existing?.deleted === true;

  if (!isExpired) {
    console.log("  → Current Primary is still valid. Skipping promotion.");
    return res.status(200).json({ status: "skipped", reason: "primary_still_valid" });
  }
}
```

